# Kernel Best Practices

## Always clean up browsers

Delete browsers when done. Use `try/finally` to ensure cleanup even on errors. Set `timeout_seconds` as a safety net.

```typescript
const browser = await kernel.browsers.create({ timeout_seconds: 300 });
try {
  // ... work
} finally {
  await kernel.browsers.deleteByID(browser.session_id);
}
```

## Use stealth mode for real websites

Enable `stealth: true` when accessing any website that might have bot detection. Most production websites do.

## Set timeouts

Always set `timeout_seconds` when creating browsers. This prevents orphaned browsers from running indefinitely and incurring costs. Use the shortest timeout that allows your task to complete.

## Use profiles for authenticated sessions

Don't hard-code credentials in automation scripts. Use Kernel browser profiles to persist login sessions across browser instances.

## Choose the right approach

- **Playwright Execution API** (`execute_playwright_code`): Best for simple, self-contained scripts that run against a single page. No local Playwright installation needed.
- **SDK + CDP connection**: Best for complex multi-step automations, when you need local file access, or when running long sessions.

## Handle errors gracefully

Wrap browser operations in try/catch blocks. Network errors, timeouts, and selector mismatches are common in browser automation. Always ensure browser cleanup runs regardless of errors.

## Use appropriate proxies

For sites with IP-based blocking, use proxies. Quality ranking: mobile > residential > ISP > datacenter. Match proxy quality to the target site's detection sophistication.

## Don't leave browsers idle

Browsers consume resources. Create them when needed, use them promptly, and delete them when done. Avoid creating browsers far in advance of when they'll be used.
